<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-08-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-08-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="283" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d283">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.428/534</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The British Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-08-29"><hi rend="italic">August 29,
                                        1919</hi></date>.</dateline>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 636</seg></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I duly brought to the notice of the
                                Canadian Government the contents of your Note No. 357 of the 25th
                                instant, informing me of a clerical error in the text of the Sockeye
                                Salmon Convention.</p>
                            <p>I have now the honour to inform you that I have received a telegram
                                from the Governor General of Canada stating that the Government of
                                Canada concurs in the corrections.</p>
                            <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">R. C.
                                Lindsay</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>